What is API?
    APIs are mechanisms that enables two software components to communicate with each other using a set of definitions and protocols.

Different types of API's?

    public API: These are open to the public and may be used by anyone
    private API: These are internal to an enterprise and only used for connecting systems and data within the business
    partner API: These are only accessible by authorized external developers to aid business to business partnerships.
    composite API: These combine two or more different APIs to address

Session: Server side stored the client information (server memory)
cookie: When server sent back with SessionId then client browser store this information.

API Gateway:
    Single entry point that routes clients requests to the appropriate microservices.
    Responsible for:
        Routes requests
        Handles authentication
        Applies rate limiting
        Logs requests
Observability:
    Provides visibility into system behaviour through logging,monitoring and tracing.

    Centralized logging
    Performance monitoring
    Request tracing across services

Stateful VS Stateless:
    Stateful systems remember past interactions(maintaining session data),while stateless systems treat each request independently with no memory of prior actions. In practice,stateful designs are useful for personalized experiences like shopping carts, while stateless designs are better for scalability and reliability ,such as REST APIs.

    📌 Real-Time Examples
            Stateful Examples
            Shopping Cart on Amazon: When you add items, the server remembers your cart until checkout. If the server didn’t maintain state, your cart would reset every time you refreshed the page.

            Online Banking: Once logged in, the server keeps track of your session so you don’t need to re-enter credentials for every action.

            Multiplayer Games: Game servers track player positions, scores, and progress continuously.

            Stateless Examples
                REST APIs: Each API call must include all necessary authentication (like tokens) because the server doesn’t remember previous calls.

            HTTP Protocol: Every request (e.g., loading a webpage) is independent; the server doesn’t know if two requests come from the same user unless cookies or tokens are used.

            DNS Queries: Each query for a domain name is independent; the server doesn’t remember past lookups.

            ⚖️ When to Use Each
                    Use Stateful when personalization, continuity, or long-running interactions are required (e.g., e-commerce, banking, gaming).

                    Use Stateless when scalability, fault tolerance, and simplicity are priorities (e.g., APIs, microservices, cloud-native apps).

            🚨 Risks & Trade-offs
            Stateful Systems: More complex to scale, risk of session loss if servers fail, higher memory usage.

            Stateless Systems: Require clients to send more data with each request, can feel less “personalized” without additional mechanisms like tokens or cookies.

            👉 In short: Stateful = memory + continuity, Stateless = independence + scalability. For modern distributed systems (like microservices), stateless is often preferred, but stateful is essential for user-centric applications like shopping and banking.

            🔑 Key Differences Between Stateful and Stateless
                    Aspect	    Stateful	                                                        Stateless
                    Definition	Server maintains client session data across requests.	            Each request is independent; no session data stored on server.
                    Memory Use	Requires server memory or database to store state.	                No memory required; all context must be sent with each request.
                    Scalability	Harder to scale (session data must be synchronized across servers).	Easier to scale (servers can handle requests independently).
                    Reliability	If server crashes, session data may be lost.	                    No dependency on server memory; requests can be routed anywhere.
                    Examples	Online banking login, shopping cart, multiplayer games.	            REST APIs, DNS, HTTP requests, microservices.
